  "prompt": "What is the best way to remove permanent marker from a countertop?",
  "response": "Removing permanent marker from a countertop can be tricky, but there are several effective methods you can try, depending on the type of countertop material. Here are some safe and effective ways:\n\n### For Non-Porous Countertops (e.g., Laminate, Quartz, Solid Surface):\n1. **Rubbing Alcohol (Isopropyl Alcohol):**\n   - Apply rubbing alcohol to a cotton ball or cloth.\n   - Gently rub the marker stain until it lifts.\n   - Wipe the area clean with a damp cloth.\n\n2. **Acetone (Nail Polish Remover):**\n   - Apply a small amount of acetone to a cotton ball or cloth.\n   - Test on a small, inconspicuous area first to ensure it won\u2019t damage the surface.\n   - Gently rub the stain until it\u2019s gone.\n   - Wipe clean with a damp cloth and mild soap.\n\n3. **Magic Eraser (Melamine Foam):**\n   - Dampen the Magic Eraser slightly with water.\n   - Gently scrub the stain in small, circular motions.\n   - Rinse the area with water.\n\n### For Porous Countertops (e.g., Granite, Marble, Soapstone):\n1. **Baking Soda Paste:**\n   - Mix baking soda with a small amount of water to form a thick paste.\n   - Apply the paste to the stain and let it sit for a few minutes.\n   - Gently scrub with a soft cloth or sponge.\n   - Rinse thoroughly with water.\n\n2. **Non-Acetone Nail Polish Remover:**\n   - Use a non-acetone nail polish remover to avoid damaging the surface.\n   - Apply a small amount to a cloth and gently rub the stain.\n   - Wipe clean with a damp cloth.\n\n3. **Hydrogen Peroxide:**\n   - Apply a small amount of hydrogen peroxide to a cloth.\n   - Gently blot the stain, avoiding vigorous scrubbing.\n   - Rinse the area with water.\n\n### General Tips:\n- **Test First:** Always test your chosen method on a small, hidden area of the countertop to ensure it won\u2019t cause damage.\n- **Act Quickly:** The sooner you address the stain, the easier it will be to remove.\n- **Avoid Harsh Abrasives:** Scrubbing too hard or using abrasive cleaners can scratch or damage the countertop surface.\n\nIf you\u2019re unsure about the material of your countertop or the best approach, consult the manufacturer\u2019s cleaning guidelines or seek professional advice.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
